<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
@N{{}}@HI{{noyouda}} is used at the end of a sentence to liken one noun to another.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{ano@KJ{{ill^Inst.}}ha@KT{{hoteru}}noyouda.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      That hospital is like a hotel
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
@N{{}}@HI{{noyouna}} is an adjectival phrase used to describe a following noun.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{rice*field^in}}sanha@KT{{hoteru}}noyouna@KJ{{ill^Inst.}}ni@KJ{{enter^Inst.}}shiteiru.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Mr. Tanaka is in a hospital like a hotel.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
@N{{}}@HI{{noyouni}} is the form used to modify a verb or an adjective.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{rice*field^in}}sanga@KJ{{enter^Inst.}}ha@KT{{hoteru}}noyounikireida.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      The hospital Mr. takana is in is as nice as a hotel.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
The form @N{{}}@HI{{noyouna}} is often used to describe something by citing an example.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{husband}}ha,@KT{{kae-}}noyouna@KJ{{simplicity^simple}}na@KJ{{fee^logic}}shika@KJ{{make}}remasen.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      My husband can only cook simple dishes like curry.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
@HI{{marude}} can appear before @N{{}}@HI{{noyou}} and acts to emphasise the similarity.

<ol>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{ano@KJ{{lake}}ha@KJ{{large}}kikute,marude@KJ{{sea}}noyoudesu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      That lake is so big it's like the sea.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{ano@KJ{{lake}}hamarude@KJ{{sea}}noyouni@KJ{{large}}kiidesu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      That lake is as large as the sea.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</ol>
</p>

